they consume.

30:28.860 --> 30:32.731 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But first: a sobering new
development with
superbugs and public health
concerns about

30:32.831 --> 30:35.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the limited effect of
antibiotics.

30:35.100 --> 30:40.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the first time in the U.S.,
a person has
been found to be carrying a
strain of E. coli

30:40.739 --> 30:45.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that's resistant to antibiotics
of last resort.
The Washington Post reported the
strain was

30:45.610 --> 30:50.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
discovered last month in a
49-year-old Pennsylvania
woman. She was resistant to
Colistin. And

30:50.649 --> 30:56.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
researchers said it -- quote --
"heralds the
emergence of a truly
pan-drug-resistant bacteria."

30:56.555 --> 31:00.559 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Dr. Beth Bell is with the
Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention. And she
is now working

31:00.659 --> 31:05.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with Pennsylvania officials.
She's the director
of the National Center for
Emerging and Zoonotic

31:05.363 --> 31:06.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Infectious Diseases.

31:06.832 --> 31:07.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thanks for joining us.

31:08.066 --> 31:10.502 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
First, how -- what is so
distinct about these
findings?

31:10.602 --> 31:12.437 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DR. BETH BELL, Director,
National Center for
Emerging and Zoonotic Infectious
Diseases:

31:12.537 --> 31:16.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Colistin is an antibiotic that
we have already
had for quite a long time, but
we use it as

31:16.374 --> 31:18.310 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a last line.

31:18.410 --> 31:23.181 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, it's our drug of last
resort. And so when
patients are infected with some
of these superbugs

31:23.281 --> 31:28.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that we have talked about
before, where the
strain is resistant to pretty
much every antibiotic,

31:28.787 --> 31:32.124 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we rely on Colistin as the last
resort.

31:32.224 --> 31:38.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we find here in this
patient, the
bacteria that infected this
patient, is that

31:38.196 --> 31:46.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
her strain contains one of these
mobile genes
that confers resistance to
Colistin. So, because

31:46.772 --> 31:52.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bacteria can spread these mobile
genes among
themselves, it sets off a
situation where

31:52.778 --> 31:58.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we can see a bacteria that's
resistant to
every known antibiotic. And, of
course, that

31:58.350 --> 32:01.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a very frightening prospect
for all of
us.

32:01.286 --> 32:02.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Right.

32:03.088 --> 32:05.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, when I am go to the
pharmacy, and I'm
prescribed something like
azithromycin or

32:05.457 --> 32:09.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
something, it's pretty low on
the scale of
the arsenal that doctors have.
So, this is

32:09.661 --> 32:13.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the top end. There is nothing
after this.
That means that the patient is
untreatable,

32:13.899 --> 32:17.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that means there is a, what,
greater chance
that they might die because of
this?

32:17.936 --> 32:19.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DR. BETH BELL: Sure.

32:19.905 --> 32:24.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's -- we luckily haven't
seen actual
bacteria that are resistant to
every single

32:24.442 --> 32:28.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
antibiotic here in the United
States. But
there are reports of this in
other parts of

32:28.747 --> 32:34.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the world, and these patients
have a very
high mortality rate. It's
extremely difficult

32:34.286 --> 32:38.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to treat them. And, again, this
raises the
specter of a post-antibiotic
era.

32:38.356 --> 32:41.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right, so
how do bugs
get this strong?

32:41.927 --> 32:47.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DR. BETH BELL: You know,
bacteria are just
really, really smart. Microbes
have learned

32:47.165 --> 32:52.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
